  "prompt": "I didn't kiss on the first date, is this bad and what should I do from this point on?",
  "response": "Not kissing on the first date is completely normal and not necessarily a bad thing. People have different comfort levels and timelines when it comes to physical intimacy, and what\u2019s most important is that both you and your date felt comfortable and enjoyed the time spent together. Here are a few things you can consider moving forward:\n\n1. **Communication**: If you\u2019re interested in continuing to see this person, consider reaching out to them. You can express your enjoyment of the date and indicate your desire to see them again.\n\n2. **Be Yourself**: Don't feel pressured to follow any specific rules about dating. Just be yourself and let things develop naturally. It\u2019s important to let the relationship progress at a pace that feels comfortable for both of you.\n\n3. **Plan Another Date**: Suggest another outing or activity that you can do together. The more time you spend together, the more comfortable you may both feel, which can lead to physical affection when the time is right.\n\n4. **Gauge Their Interest**: Pay attention to their signals and responsiveness. If they seem interested in you and enjoy spending time together, that\u2019s a good sign to proceed.\n\n5. **Listen to Your Instincts**: Trust your feelings about the situation. If you feel a connection and want to progress, that\u2019s great. If you feel unsure, it\u2019s perfectly okay to take your time.\n\nUltimately, every relationship is unique, and there\u2019s no right or wrong approach. Focus on building a connection and see where things go from there!",
